items.title: Two boys fatally stabbed in Melbourne's west potentially victims of mistaken identity
items.standfirst: The friends were allegedly set upon by up to eight masked men in an attack which police said has the "hallmarks of a youth gang crime".
items.content: A 12-year-old boy and a 15-year-old boy killed in a suspected machete attack in Melbourne's west overnight were potentially ambushed in a case of mistaken identity.The two friends were walking from a bus stop in Cobblebank last night just before 8pm with a third friend when they were set upon by up to eight masked men in an attack which police said has the "hallmarks of a youth gang crime".Police initially believed the stabbings were the result of a targeted attack. READ MORE: Man dies after early morning shooting in Melbourne's CBDEmergency services were called to the scene where they found the 12-year-old boy.Paramedics tried to resuscitate him but he could not be saved.Victoria Police duty crime officer Graham Banks said a short time later Dau Akueng, the 15-year-old friend, was found dead nearby on Cobble Street as a result of "significant injuries consistent with being stabbed".READ MORE: Beaches closed after surfer killed in shark attackHe added the 12-year-old and Akueng were not gang members. "Both murders are linked to the same offenders," Banks said."Witness and CCTV vision shows the murders were committed by a large group of male offenders who appear to be covered with face masks."They fled the scene in a vehicle that is yet to be identified and vision shows that they were armed with machetes."While the investigation is in its early stages, police believe the attacks have "the hallmarks of a youth gang crime"."It is one of the most horrific crimes in a substantial and growing list of crimes of this nature," Banks said."Police are appealing for witnesses to come forward and that includes people who will know these offenders."Given the time of night, it will be anticipated that a number of vehicles were around that vicinity and enough of those cars will have dashcam footage.READ MORE:Teenage boy dies after 'stolen car' crashes during police pursuit "We appeal for people who will have knowledge of this crime and that will include people known to the offenders to come forward."You can do it anonymously but you can also report it formally."Banks said police would work to determine a motive for the stabbings."When we see crimes of this nature sometimes occur, there has been occasion where people have been targeted by mistaken identity," Banks said."There is potential that the offenders know these people and they've been specifically targeted as well, but there's also clearly a possibility that it's been a case of mistaken identity and that this is what has occurred." READ MORE: China criticises Australian and Canadian warships transiting Taiwan Strait The masked men are believed to be older than the victims. Akueng's father said he needed answers for his son.."This is a basketball player, he's not a criminal," Elbino Akueng said."I'm talking on behalf of my community, this is happening to us."In the last month, we have buried four kids, similar incidents keep happening, but there's no answer from police." Akueng has been remembered as a bright and talented young basketballer. Collingwood Basketball Association (CBA) general manager Trent Pearson said he was a "much-loved member" of the club."He was a highly talented player and referee with a cheerful personality who touched all those he interacted with over many years," Pearson said."Dau had a smile and confidence that were infectious and his love for basketball and being around his friends will be sorely missed.""As a club we are devastated by his passing. I've spoken today to the family and our focus now, is supporting them and our club members in coming to terms with the tragic loss of a beautiful young man."CBA vice president Duré De Winter said Dau "brightened everyone's day with his smile" and spoke of his maturity on and off the court." We are heartbroken to lose such a beautiful young man. Our thoughts and condolences go to his family and community, they are a strong and beautiful community," Winter said."We are so sorry for their loss."Police and the NSW State Emergency Service spent the night in the street gathering evidence. "The exact circumstances surrounding the deaths are still being determined but are believed to be connected," Victoria Police said in a statement earlier today."At this time police are treating it as a targeted attack and the investigation remains ongoing."Anyone with information is urged to contact Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 000.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. items.content: A man has died at Sydney Airport after an accident at the freight terminal.Emergency services were called to the airport in south Sydney at around 10:30am this morning after a freight handler was reportedly struck by a vehicle.Paramedics treated the man, who is believed to be in his 40s, but he died at the scene.READ MORE: Man dies after early morning shooting in Melbourne's CBDThe incident is not being treated as suspicious.Sydney Airport said they were saddened by the incident confirmed they were offering support to airlines and authorities. "Everyone at Sydney Airport is deeply saddened by the fatal incident involving an airfreight worker earlier this morning," they told 9News.com.au.READ MORE: Devastating Father's Day after man killed in shark attack at popular Sydney beach "Our thoughts are with the worker's family, friends and colleagues during this incredibly difficult time.
